      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for that. but i'm still a bit lost on how to actually use it with sharps and flats. can u explain the pattern? like how do i know if a key has sharps or flats just by looking at where it is on the circle?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Of course! Let’s break it down. The circle of fifths arranges keys in a circular pattern where each key is a perfect fifth apart. To determine if a key has sharps or flats, follow these rules:\n\n1. Move clockwise from C major:\n   - C major is your starting point, with no sharps or flats.\n   - G is the next key, one sharp (F♯).\n   - D, which follows, adds another: two sharps (F♯, C♯).\n   - A takes it up by three: three sharps (F♯, C♯, G♯).\n   - The circle continues, with E having four and then B with five sharps.\n   - Starting from C, moving clockwise, the first sharp a key notes: F♯.\n\n2. Moving counter-clockwise from C major:\n   - F♯ is the first symmetrically placed note and has five flats: B♭, E♭, A♭, D♭, G♭.\n   - You’ll continue looking for the subsequent flats: E♭, A♭, D♭, G♭, B♭.\n   -",
